<div id="review_989781669" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/989781669" />
    <a title="Jonathan" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/31745815-jonathan"><img alt="Jonathan" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1609515814p2/31745815.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/989781669?book_show_action=true">Jul 08, 2014</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Jonathan" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Jonathan" href="/user/show/31745815-jonathan">Jonathan</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780140037395" href="/book/show/1307545.August_1914">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/31745815-jonathan?shelf=classics">classics</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer989781669" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16274113195926659145">It&apos;s hard not to add to all the comments that have already been made on this book. Yes it was a marathon and a tough read, but I can&apos;t help but appreciate the man&apos;s genius while doing so. It&apos;s difficult to recommend, but also difficult to give a low rating as a result. I learned a lot, personally, from reading this.<br/><br/>Reading some of the background of the battle described from other accounts, it&apos;s disturbing to think how pivotal the battle of Tannenburg was to world history. The German army had the</span>
  <span id="freeText16274113195926659145" style="display:none">It's hard not to add to all the comments that have already been made on this book. Yes it was a marathon and a tough read, but I can't help but appreciate the man's genius while doing so. It's difficult to recommend, but also difficult to give a low rating as a result. I learned a lot, personally, from reading this.<br /><br />Reading some of the background of the battle described from other accounts, it's disturbing to think how pivotal the battle of Tannenburg was to world history. The German army had the brilliant strategy of capturing Paris and fighting off the Western Front, before turning to defend herself against Russia, who as a large country would need time to get their troops together. Realizing this, the Russians had mobilized far quicker than expected and began to march on Berlin knowing that the more efficient German army would be weaker at this point. So in the context of this particular account, if the Russians had won this, they would have reached Berlin in time to force a German surrender on all fronts. <br /><br />Having said this, I'm not sure that Solzhenitsyn really considered the Russian success of this battle ever being a plausible conclusion; especially when we see the final war council in the close of the book with Colonel Vorotyntsev, the only sensible person there, being dismissed. It was always destined to fail due to the characters and infrastructure that were in place. In this light, while the Germans were surprised at the speed of the offensive, ultimately, they were right. The Russians simply couldn't get it together in time. <br /><br />In spite of all the above, nevertheless, hindsight frustratingly teaches that it could still have been won. There were simple mistakes made. For example, the radio communications were open, so the Germans knew exactly where each Russian unit was. Russia's first army did not follow up their victory and let the German units reinforce the other units fighting Russia's second army. Rather, they sat and waited unwittingly letting the second army be outnumbered, outgunned and decimated. <br /><br />It's also disturbing to think that with all the clever and efficient strategizing done by the German Headquarters, the outcome of the battle was decisively won by a German general of Huguenot origins, who disobeyed orders with Gallic flare and effectively swept behind the Russian forces, preventing them from regrouping and forcing a surrender. <br /><br />Most disturbing of all, nearly everyone agrees, is the overall narrative of how the Russian army was ultimately undone by echelons of incompetence, miscommunication and egos, which get worse the more we journey up to the top. With this aspect, Solzhenitsyn's panoramas the whole battle with exasperation and in doing so shows how it created so much space for Communism to rise.</span>
  <a data-text-id="16274113195926659145" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

